    <h2>MS-Excel (Spreadsheet)</h2>
    <h3>Introduction</h3>
    <p>
        MS-Excel is a spreadsheet software in the Microsoft Office suite that allows users to store, organize, and analyze numerical and text data. It is part of the MS-Office package and presents information clearly. It can perform mathematical calculations using formulas and equations and convert spreadsheet data into various charts like bar graphs and columns. Excel is used for calculations such as salary sheets, income and expense statements, balance sheets, and budget preparation. Some application areas of Excel include:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>Basic mathematical calculations.</li>
        <li>Financial modeling and analysis.</li>
        <li>Statistical analysis.</li>
        <li>Scientific and engineering calculations.</li>
        <li>Graphic presentation and more.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The extension of MS-Excel files is “.xlsx” and “.xls”.</p>

    <h3>Common Terminologies Used in Spreadsheet</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Worksheet (Spreadsheet):</strong> A collection of rows and columns used to list, organize, and calculate data.</li>
        <li><strong>Workbook:</strong> Files used in spreadsheets, consisting of several worksheets.</li>
        <li><strong>Cell:</strong> The intersection of rows and columns, referred to by column letter followed by row number (e.g., C2).</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Features of MS-Excel</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Facilitates working in multiple worksheets at a time.</li>
        <li>Allows creation of different types of charts and graphs.</li>
        <li>Organizes and manages large volumes of data.</li>
        <li>Performs calculations automatically using custom formulas.</li>
        <li>Easily sorts data in ascending and descending order.</li>
        <li>Supports high-level features like object linking and embedding.</li>
        <li>Formats data to enhance attractiveness using tools like font size and color.</li>
        <li>Includes internet features such as web toolbars.</li>
        <li>Stores data electronically in any storage medium.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>MS-PowerPoint (Presentation)</h2>
    <h3>Introduction</h3>
    <p>
        PowerPoint is presentation software in the Microsoft Office suite that allows users to create dynamic and professional presentations using predefined layouts, themes, and templates. A PowerPoint presentation consists of a series of slides containing information to communicate with an audience, including text, images, graphs, charts, videos, audio, and more. The extension of PowerPoint files is “.ppt”, while later versions use “.pptx”. Other alternatives to MS-PowerPoint include Magic Point, Apple Keynote, IBM Lotus, and Harvard Graphics.
    </p>

    <h3>Features of MS-PowerPoint</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Formatting of data enhances the document's attractiveness and interactivity.</li>
        <li>Supports simple computing operations like cut, copy, paste, find, and replace.</li>
        <li>Allows use of predefined layouts, themes, and templates for faster development.</li>
        <li>Enables slide transitions and effects for presentations.</li>
        <li>Custom animations can be created for specific elements.</li>
        <li>Supports both internal and external hyperlinks.</li>
        <li>Allows the use of various charts and graphs to convey information.</li>
        <li>Includes internet features such as web toolbars and online help.</li>
    </ul>
